ce:section.ce:para:
To investigate the molecule interaction between CDs and Cur, FTIR and XPS analysis were taken. In Fig. 3a, peaks around 3410 and 1701 cm−1 are respectively assigned to the O-H/N-H stretching vibration and CO stretching vibration that derived from CDs(Chen et al., 2022; Li, Kang, et al., 2021). Stretching vibration from 1400 to 1650 cm−1 can be identified as Cur characteristic peaks(Liu et al., 2023). Obviously, peaks within 1400 to 1650 cm−1 gradually become apparent with the increasing Cur load rate. Thus, Cur-CDs-3 was selected as representative samples to be further compared with CDs, Cur, and a physical mixture of CDs with Cur (Fig. 3b). For CDs, peaks around 1635 and 1567 cm−1 are assigned to the O=C-NH bend, while peaks at 1394 and 1067 cm−1 are attributed to CN and C-O-C bends respectively(Li et al., 2020; Qu et al., 2022). For samples that contains Cur, the peak at 1625 cm−1 that associated with CC stretching of aromatic hydrocarbon groups is a characteristic peak for Cur (Liu et al., 2023; Perera et al., 2021). Interestingly, for Cur-CDs, CO bend that derived from Cur negatively shifts from 1602 to 1588 cm−1, representing that the molecular interactions between CDs and Cur might occur on the CO bond of Cur. A stable hydrogen bond is formed between CDs and Cur, which is conductive to the improving aqueous solubility of Cur in Cur-CDs nanocapsule (Liu et al., 2023). Meanwhile, the loss of OH stretching peak in the FTIR spectrum of Cur-CDs at 3499 cm−1 also supports the formation of hydrogen bond between Cur and CDs. Owing to that parts of Cur are encapsulated inside the CDs (
                           Fig. 4

                        ), the stretching vibration within the ranges of 1170–1260 cm−1 (OH bend) and 1415–1470 cm−1 (O-H/O-CH bend) that originating from Cur significantly weakened (Perera et al., 2021) (Fig. 3b). In addition, 1HNMS spectra analysis was conducted. In Fig. 3c, using methyl sulfoxide as solution, typical chemical shifts at 3.84, 6.07, 6.78, 6.84, 7.15, 7.33, 7.57 and 9.66 ppm can be found, which are attributed to the trans,trans-1,7-bis(4-hydroxy-3-methoxyphenyl)-1,6-heptadiene-3,5-dione. Compared to pure Cur, shift at 9.66 ppm in the 1HNMR spectrum of Cur-CDs that assigned to phenol bond of Cur negatively shifts to 9.55 ppm (Fig. 3d), which is likely due to the formation of hydrogen bond between phenol bond of Cur and CO bond of CDs (Liu et al., 2023).
